From: dune conda packaging
Subject: [PATCH] src_module: build TRACE.ko only when WANT_KMOD is requested

TRACE's top CMakeLists unconditionally add_subdirectory(src_module), and
src_module/CMakeLists.txt builds the TRACE.ko kernel module whenever
/lib/modules/$(uname -r)/build exists. On a build host WITHOUT kernel headers
(CI, the FNAL cluster) that check is false and the module is silently skipped; on
a host WITH kernel headers (an Ubuntu dev machine) it tries to build TRACE.ko and
fails (e.g. kernel Makefile arch quirk: "arch/64/Makefile: No such file or
directory"). A conda package must never contain a host-kernel-specific .ko, so
make the module build opt-in via -DWANT_KMOD=ON (a flag TRACE already references).
Default (unset) => never build the module, independent of the build host. The
else-branch's existing WANT_KMOD FATAL_ERROR still fires if a user requests the
module without kernel headers.

--- a/src_module/CMakeLists.txt
+++ b/src_module/CMakeLists.txt
@@ -7,7 +7,13 @@

 message("KVERS is ${KVERS}")

-if (EXISTS /lib/modules/${KVERS}/build)
+# Build the kernel module ONLY when explicitly requested (-DWANT_KMOD=ON). A conda
+# package must never ship a host-kernel-specific TRACE.ko: on a build host that has
+# kernel headers (/lib/modules/$(uname -r)/build present, e.g. a dev machine) the
+# original unconditional check would try to build it and fail. Gating on WANT_KMOD
+# makes the conda build host-independent; the else-branch below still errors if a
+# user asks for WANT_KMOD without kernel headers.
+if (WANT_KMOD AND EXISTS /lib/modules/${KVERS}/build)
     add_custom_command(
 		OUTPUT ${CMAKE_CURRENT_BINARY_DIR}/../module/${KVERS}/TRACE.ko
 		COMMAND ${CMAKE_COMMAND} -E copy ${CMAKE_CURRENT_SOURCE_DIR}/Makefile ${CMAKE_CURRENT_BINARY_DIR}
